  Warning                                                         9920 1451   85
==================================================================9920 1451   86
  MF/MT combinations used to define ALL electron interaction data 9920 1451   87
  are newly defined MF/MT numbers for ENDF/B-VI that did not exist9920 1451   88
  in earlier versions of ENDF/B.                                  9920 1451   89
==================================================================9920 1451   90
  Definition of Data                                              9920 1451   91
==================================================================9920 1451   92
  Cross Sections (MF=23)                                          9920 1451   93
==================================================================9920 1451   94
1) The total electron interaction cross section is given          9920 1451   95
   explicitly as MF/MT=23/501. It is the sum of scatter,          9920 1451   96
   bremsstrahlung, excitation and ionization cross sections,      9920 1451   97
   i.e., MT = 526, 527, 528, and 534 through 572.                 9920 1451   98
2) The total electron ionization cross section is given           9920 1451   99
   explicitly as MF/MT=23/522. It is the sum of the aubshell      9920 1451  100
   cross sections, i.e., all MT = 534 through 572.                9920 1451  101
==================================================================9920 1451  102
  Angular and Energy Distributions (MF=26)                        9920 1451  103
==================================================================9920 1451  104
3) For Large Angle Scatter (MT=525), angular distributions of     9920 1451  105
   electrons are tabulated between cosine = -1.0 and 0.999999.    9920 1451  106
   Between +0.99999 and +1.0 it is analytically defined as        9920 1451  107
   Coulomb scattering,                                            9920 1451  108
                                                                  9920 1451  109
   d(sig)/d(cos) = A/[eta+(1.0 - cos)]^2                          9920 1451  110
                                                                  9920 1451  111
   where the shielding parameter (eta) is defined by the          9920 1451  112
   Steve Seltzer expression (see, ref. 1), and (A) is the         9920 1451  113
   normalization factor for the integral +0.99999 to +1.0.        9920 1451  114
   Electron elastic scatter means no energy loss, so only         9920 1451  115
   angular distributions are giving.                              9920 1451  116
4) For bremsstrahlung, both the outgoing electron and photon are  9920 1451  117
   described. The photon energy spectra are given, but angular    9920 1451  118
   distributions are not; these can be analytically defined by a  9920 1451  119
   number of different methods. For the electron, average energy  9920 1451  120
   loss is given. The electron is assumed to continue along its   9920 1451  121
   original direction of travel, so angular distributions are not 9920 1451  122
   given. WARNING - bremsstrahlung is a three body process,       9920 1451  123
   involving an electron, a photon, and an atom - so that you     9920 1451  124
   cannot use energy or momentum correlation to simply relate     9920 1451  125
   the secondary electron and the emitted photon.                 9920 1451  126
5) For excitation, the average energy loss of the electron is     9920 1451  127
   given. The electron is assumed to continue along its original  9920 1451  128
   direction of travel, so angular distributions are not given.   9920 1451  129
6) For Ionization, the spectra of electrons is given. The electron9920 1451  130
   is assumed to continue along its original direction of travel, 9920 1451  131
   so angular distributions are not given. In ionization two      9920 1451  132
   identical electrons emerge; the incident electron, and an      9920 1451  133
   electron ejected by the atom [thereby ionizing the atom]. Since9920 1451  134
   the two particles are indistinquishable, we define the electron9920 1451  135
   with the lower energy to be that ejected by the atom, and the  9920 1451  136
   electron with the higher energy to be the incident electron.   9920 1451  137
   The energy of the two electrons is exactly correlated by energy9920 1451  138
   conservation: initial incident electron energy = binding energy9920 1451  139
   of the ejected electron, plus the kinetic energy of the ejected9920 1451  140
   and the secondary incident electron. Therefore only the spectra9920 1451  141
   of the lower energy, ejected electron is given. The energy of  9920 1451  142
   the secondary incident electron should be defined to conserve  9920 1451  143
   energy, as described above. The energy lost by the incident    9920 1451  144
   electron is the sum of the binding and kinetic energy of the   9920 1451  145
   ejected electron.                                              9920 1451  146
7) Relaxation of ionized atoms back to neutrality is not described9920 1451  147
   here; it is described in the companion Evaluated Atomic Data   9920 1451  148
   Library (EADL).                                                9920 1451  149
